# configuration.md

## Configuration Notes

This lab was completed using two physical Cisco Catalyst switches. Rather than copying commands from a simulator, I configured the devices manually through the console connection and verified each step along the way.

### VLANs Created

| VLAN | Name    |
| ---- | ------- |
| 10   | USERS   |
| 20   | PHONES  |
| 30   | SERVERS |
| 99   | MGMT    |

---

## SW1 Configuration

Configured VLANs and established an 802.1Q trunk to SW2.

### Trunk Port

```cisco
interface GigabitEthernet0/48
 description Trunk to SW2
 switchport mode trunk
 switchport trunk allowed vlan 10,20,30,99
 no shutdown
```

---

## SW2 Configuration

Configured matching VLANs and trunk settings.

### Trunk Port

```cisco
interface GigabitEthernet0/4
 description Trunk to SW1
 switchport mode trunk
 switchport trunk allowed vlan 10,20,30,99
 no shutdown
```

---

## Saving Configuration

After verifying functionality, configurations were saved using:

```cisco
copy running-config startup-config
```

### Takeaways

* Consistency between switches is important.
* Trunk links only carry VLANs that are explicitly allowed.
* Verifying configurations is just as important as applying them.
